The paper focuses on the development of an augmented reality tourism app through user-centred design, which involves designing interfaces that are usable and intuitive for users. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the use of graphics and maps to overlay information on natural environments, which suggests that it may also belong to the Graphics (cs.GR) sub-category. The paper also discusses the challenges of designing interfaces that are secure and protect user privacy, which suggests that it may belong to the Cybersecurity (cs.CYBER) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper involves the use of information retrieval techniques to identify points of interest for tourists, which suggests that it may also belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of mobile devices to deliver augmented reality experiences, which suggests that it may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
